<theorem xml:id="lecture-notes-thm-exponential-functions-a-lt-1">
  <title>Exponential Functions with <m>0 &lt; a &lt; 1</m></title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>f(x) = a^x</m> be an exponential function where <m>0 &lt; a &lt; 1</m>. The graph of <m>f</m> has the following properties:
      <ul>
        <li><p>Domain: <m>\left( -\infty, \infty \right)</m></p></li>
        <li><p>Range: <m>\left( 0, \infty \right)</m></p></li>
        <li><p><m>y</m>-intercept: <m>(0, 1)</m>.</p></li>
        <li>
          <p>
            End Behavior:
            <ul>
              <li><p>As <m>x \to \infty, f(x) \to 0</m>. This implies the <m>x</m>-axis is a horizontal asymptote.</p></li>
              <li><p>As <m>x \to -\infty, f(x) \to \infty</m></p></li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li><p>The function is decreasing on <m>\left( -\infty, \infty \right)</m>.</p></li>
      </ul>
    </p>

    <figure xml:id="lecture-notes-fig-graph-exp-a-lt-1">
      <caption>
        The graph of <m>f(x) = a^x</m> where <m>0 &lt; a &lt; 1</m>. 
        The sample points <m>(-2, \frac{1}{a^2})</m>, <m>(-1, \frac{1}{a})</m>, <m>(0, 1)</m>, <m>(1, a)</m>, and <m>(2, a^2)</m> are plotted.
      </caption>
      <image source="chapter-8/graph-exp-a-lt-1.png" width="50%" decorative="yes">
        <shortdescription>Graph of f(x)=a^x for 0&lt;a&lt;1</shortdescription>
      </image>
    </figure>

  </statement>
</theorem>


