<definition xml:id="lecture-notes-def-logarithm">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>f(x)=b^x</m> be an exponential function with <m>b&gt;0</m> and <m>b\neq 1</m>. 
            The inverse function of <m>f</m> is called the <term>logarithmic function</term> with base <m>b</m> and is denoted by <m>y=\log_b(x)</m>. 
            This means that <m>y=\log_b(x)</m> if and only if <m>b^y=x</m>.
            In other words, <m>log_b(x)</m> is the exponent to which we must raise <m>b</m> to obtain the value <m>x</m>.
        </p>
    </statement>
</definition>
<note>
  <title>Parentheses in Logarithmic Expressions</title>

  <p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p>
          When you take a logarithm of a single term, it is common practice to drop the parentheses like this:
          <m>\log_b(x)=\log_b x</m>. I will never drop the parentheses in my lecture notes.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Taking the logarithm of an expression with more than one term always requires parentheses:
          <m>\log_b(x+1) \neq \log_b x + 1 = \log_b(x) + 1</m>.
        </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </p>
</note>
<corollary xml:id="lecture-notation-common-natural-log">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Two logarithmic functions are given special notation.
            <ul>
                <li><p>The logarithmic function with base 10 is called the <term>common logarithm</term> and is denoted by <m>\log(x)</m>. In other words, <m>\log(x)=\log_{10}(x)</m>.</p></li>
                <li><p>The logarithmic function with base <m>e</m> is called the <term>natural logarithm</term> and is denoted by <m>\ln(x)</m>. In other words, <m>\ln(x)=\log_{e}(x)</m>.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </p>
    </statement>
</corollary>
